Introduction

What makes one song popular and another song not as successful? The main purpose of this project is to analyze whether or not factors of the song impact the popularity. We decided to focus on dancergy, an element we made by combining danceability and energy. We wanted to see if it is possible to predict the popularity of a song based on its dancergy.

Music producers have a goal, to spread their music for many people to enjoy. Therefore, they pay a lot of attention to what makes a song successful. Knowing which factors contribute to the popularity of the song allows them to focus on creating songs that feed into these factors. By analyzing the relationship between dancergy and popularity, we will be able to determine whether or not music producers should focus on dancergy to produce a popular song.

Data Curation

Our first step was to find a suitable dataset. By looking on Kaggle, we were able to find a Spotify Tracks Dataset that includes 125,000 songs and song attributes such as popularity, duration, danceability, speechiness, liveness, energy, etc. Our first step was to find a suitable dataset. Adds a new variable dancergy

Dancergy is dervied from square rooting the product of danceability and energy

$\sqrt{danceability * energy}$

Outliers

Finds the amount of outliers in each category

In [ ]:
# Find Outliers
outlier_lists = []
for category in categories:
  q1 = tracks[category].quantile(.25)
  q3 = tracks[category].quantile(.75)
  iqr = q3 - q1
  outliers1 = tracks[tracks[category] > (q3+1.5*iqr)]
  outliers = pd.concat((outliers1, tracks[tracks[category] < (q1-1.5*iqr)]))
  outlier_lists.append(outliers)
  print(category + " has " + str(outliers.shape[0]) + " outliers")

def scatterplots(row, data):
  fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 4, figsize= (60, 40))
  i = 0
  j = 0
  for col in data.columns:
    if (col != row and (col != "explicit") and (col != "genre") and (col != "text")):
      ax[i][j].scatter(data[col], data[row])
      ax[i][j].set_title(col + " vs " + row)
      ax[i][j].title.set_size(40)
      ax[i][j].tick_params(axis='x', which='both', labelsize=20)
      ax[i][j].tick_params(axis='y', which='both', labelsize=20)
      ax[i][j].set_xlabel(col, fontsize = 20)
      ax[i][j].set_ylabel(row, fontsize = 20)
      j = 0 if j == 3 else j + 1
      i = i + 1 if j == 0 else i

A z-test to compare popularity of a sample of high dancergy songs vs population:

Null Hypothesis: The danceability and energy (danceability) of the song has no impact on the popularity of the song

Alternative Hypothesis: The danceability and energy (danceability) of the song increases the likelihood that the song is popular.

alpha: 0.05

In [ ]:
one_std_above = mean + std
filtered_high_dancergy = filtered[filtered['Dancergy'] >= one_std_above].head(30)

# Extract popularity levels into an array
popularity_array = filtered_high_dancergy['Popularity'].values

print(popularity_array)

# Method 1 : Using Z-score

sample_mean = np.mean(popularity_array)
sample_size = np.count_nonzero(popularity_array)
population_mean = describe2["popularity"]["mean"]
population_std = describe2["popularity"]["std"]
alpha = 0.05
z_score = (sample_mean-population_mean)/(population_std/math.sqrt(sample_size))
critical_value = 1.645 # from z table
print("Z SCORE: " + str(z_score))


if(z_score<critical_value):
    print('WE FAIL TO REJECT THE NULL HYPOTHESIS')
else:
    print('WE REJECT THE NULL HYPOTHESIS')

Z SCORE: 1.121232967887784
WE FAIL TO REJECT THE NULL HYPOTHESIS

To conduct our right-tailed z-test, we pulled 30 songs that had a dancergy level greater than or equal to .76. This is what we would consider "high dancergy" because it is 1 standard deviation above the average. We took the mean of popularity scores among these 30 high dancergy songs and used that in our z-score calculations. Because we obtained a z-score of 1.12, we failed to reject our null hypothesis because it is less than our critical value of 1.645. !.646 is the corresponding critical value for our alpha level of .05. We cannot conclude that high dancergy levels are correlated positively to popularity.

Based on the conclusions from our statistical methods, there is no statistically significant relationship between dancergy and population. To start, we looked at finding outliers, that could disrupt our results for center and variance. However, out of over 100,000 songs, there were only 2,000 outliers for dancergy. We believe this is acceptable. We also found, through our correlation methods, that there is a small positive correlation between dancergy and popularity. We also looked at using the central limit theorem to examine the center. We found on average songs have high dancergy and small popularity. However, when we performed our hypothesis test, we failed to reject the null hypothesis. This means that the danceability and energy (danceability) of the song has no impact on the popularity of the song despite our initial findings of a very small correlation. In order to continue our research we decided to focus more on a single genre of data so that all of the songs have a similar approach, goal. We decided to focus on electronic music because typically, these songs are more successful when they have more dance and energy.

Primary Analysis

We chose to use the regression algorithm to answer the question of how to predict a songs popularity based on its dancergy metric.

The reason we chose this algorithm is because it can predict numerical outputs based on a numerical input. Our input in this context is a songs dancergy score, and output is the songs popularity score. As stated above, we made the decision to continue with a focus on Rock music in particular. With our new dataset of dancergy to popularity of just the Rock songs, we can observe just from the plot of our data points that there is a slight positive correlation. The LinearRegression library from scikit-learn will continue by running a gradient descent on this dataset in order to minimize the error of the line we are fitting to it. Gradient descent works as a more advanced educated guess and check. It has an initial line that it measures against our data points, which yields a Residual sum of squares (RSS). It then uses the sign of the slope (+ or -) to change the coefficients of the equation of the line to hopefully yield a lower RSS than its previous iteration. It continues this until it finds a minima. The magnitude of change in coefficients depends on a parameter called the learning rate. Changing our learning rate can affect our models speed and accuracy.

def pred(x, y):
  model = LinearRegression()
  model.fit(x, y)
  return model.predict(x)

Conclusion

After applying the functions from the LinearRegression library on our dataset, we observed an average MSE between the training and test data of 123.5, and an average R^2 of .09. We believe this small value is due to the vast amount of noise. This value of MSE is not favorable, as it is quite high. It means that the residuals from our predicted line and actual points are high. However, it was never going to be low because of the vast quantity of data. The R^2 score is also unfavorable, as it is very low. Though the score is greater than zero, meaning our line fits our data better than a horizontal line would, it still does not explain much of the variance in the dataset. On the bright side, our R^2 value is much higher than the initial value we calculated in the correlation graph for R. Squaring this initial value of .026 gives an R^2 value of .000676 (.09 > .000676). It is apparent from our findings that dancergy alone is not enough to accurately predict the popularity of Rock songs, let alone songs in every other genre. In the future, we would choose to ignore all the noise and look at a much smaller dataset, perhaps only the successful songs.
